<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMUNITY NEWS: SANTA MONICA; OIL SPILL FORCES FIRM TO PAY $50,000 TO HEAL THE 
BAY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SUSAN WOODWARD 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 An oil spill in Los Angeles Harbor has brought a $50,000 windfall to Heal the 
Bay, a nonprofit environmental organization based in Santa Monica. 
</P>
<P>
 Japanese shipping firm Shinko Maritime Co. Ltd. was ordered to make the 
contribution and pay another $50,000 in fines when it pleaded no contest on 
Monday to a charge of negligence. 
</P>
<P>
 About 630 gallons of heavy oil spilled into the harbor on Aug. 9, 1993, when 
the freighter Tropical Dawn, chartered by Shinko, was refueling, said Los 
Angeles City Atty. James K. Hahn. 
</P>
<P>
 Booms that were placed around the Tropical Dawn contained most of the spill, 
but the pilings and seawall beneath about 1,600 feet of pier had to be 
steam-cleaned, Hahn said. 
</P>
<P>
 Heal the Bay spokesman Roger Gorke said he hoped the fine, ordered by Los 
Angeles Municipal Court Judge Barry Taylor, would be a deterrent. 
</P>
<P>
 "Some of these companies think that environmental pollution is just another 
cost of doing business," Gorke said. 
</P>
<P>
 Heal the Bay, which has an annual operating budget of $500,000 to $750,000, 
focuses on problems including the flow of debris that washes into the ocean 
from area streets, Gorke said. SUSAN WOODWARD 
</P>
</TEXT>
