<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMUNITY NEWS: PALOS VERDES ESTATES; DANGEROUS-ANIMAL ORDINANCE ADOPTED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JEFF KASS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Residents, police and animals have been given a new code to live by. 
</P>
<P>
 The Palos Verdes Estates City Council voted 5 to 0 on Nov. 22 to enact a 
dangerous-animal ordinance. 
</P>
<P>
 The city's Police Department took over animal regulation from the Los Angeles 
chapter of the Humane Society last year, but existing city codes did not offer 
police any guidance. 
</P>
<P>
 Police Chief Gary Johansen said the department received about six calls last 
year of dogs biting, and in some cases killing, other animals. 
</P>
<P>
 Animals that seriously injure or kill people or pets are considered dangerous, 
as are dogs maintained for the purpose of fighting, according to the ordinance. 
</P>
<P>
 Violating the ordinance is a misdemeanor, punishable by up to six months in 
jail and a $1,000 fine for the owner, said City Atty. Stephanie Scher. 
</P>
<P>
 Dangerous animals may be put to sleep or allowed to stay in the city as long 
as they are properly contained and identified. 
</P>
<P>
 Owners who disagree with police that their animals are dangerous may take 
their case to the Humane Society pound master. JEFF KASS 
</P>
</TEXT>
