<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMUNITY NEWS: ROLLING HILLS ESTATES; CITY COUNCIL NAMES BECK NEW MAYOR 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Although the mayor's gavel has changed hands in this peninsula city, don't 
expect many changes. 
</P>
<P>
 Following custom, the City Council voted 5 to 0 on Nov. 22 to make Mayor Pro 
Tem Robert Beck the next mayor.He replaces Barbara Rauch, who goes back to the 
council after a one-year mayoral term. 
</P>
<P>
 Beck, who owns a law firm in Torrance, said he has no hidden agenda and no 
special projects to push through the council. 
</P>
<P>
 "If I come up with something, I'll give you a call," he said.  
</P>
<P>
 Beck, 46, mentioned the George F Canyon Nature Center and the neighborhood 
compatibility study, which outlines the character of each neighborhood, as 
important projects. 
</P>
<P>
 The mayor's vote carries no extra weight, and his recommendations for city 
committees must be approved by the council, said City Manager Doug Prichard. 
</P>
<P>
 With Councilwoman Susan Seamans abstaining, the council selected Peter M. 
Weber as the new mayor pro tem. 
</P>
<P>
 Beck, a former planning commissioner, is serving his first four-year term on 
the council and said he expects to run again in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
 The Becks were recently honored as the South Bay's international family of the 
year. Beck and his wife, Nancy, have five children, ages 5 to 22, including two 
who were adopted from Russia in August, 1993. 
</P>
</TEXT>
