<HEADLINE>
<P>
CYCLIST GETS YEAR IN JAIL FOR STAGING ACCIDENTS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By JEANNETTE REGALADO, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A man who rigged his bicycle to fall apart upon impact in staged accidents was 
sentenced to one year in jail after he pleaded no contest Wednesday to theft 
charges, authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
 Richard Siddons, 33, of Tarzana, was first arrested Oct. 26 after police 
watched him stage two accidents with cars leaving the Ventura Freeway at DeSoto 
Avenue in Woodland Hills, according to the city attorney's office. 
</P>
<P>
 Siddons, who said he is an unemployed plumber, was sentenced in Van Nuys 
Municipal Court after he pleaded no contest to six counts of theft. He was 
ordered to begin serving his sentence immediately, said Deputy City Atty. Wayne 
Mooney. He was also ordered to pay $653 in restitution to 11 of his victims, 
Mooney added. 
</P>
<P>
 Police had received several complaints from motorists who reported being 
involved in traffic accidents with a bicyclist who asked for money -- in one 
case $75 -- to repair his bicycle after the accident, according to Mooney. 
</P>
<P>
 Siddons was identified by police after he filed a crime report accusing one of 
his victims of hit-and-run driving. Police then followed him to a Tarzana hotel 
and watched him place a red bicycle with a bent front wheel in a car and drive 
to the DeSoto off-ramp, Mooney said. 
</P>
<P>
 Mooney said Siddons adjusted the seat and front wheel of the bicycle so they 
would fly off upon impact and began riding along DeSoto Avenue and Clark Street 
near the freeway exit. He first struck a Ford Thunderbird and later a Ford 
Escort as the cars were leaving the freeway off-ramp, Mooney said. 
</P>
<P>
 Siddons was arrested after the second accident and booked for theft at the 
LAPD's Van Nuys Division. He later pleaded not guilty to the charges and was 
released on his own recognizance until his Nov. 17 trial, Mooney said. 
</P>
<P>
 After news reports of his arrest, eight more motorists contacted police to 
report being rammed by Siddons on his bicycle. More charges were filed against 
Siddons and he was arrested again on Nov. 2. 
</P>
</TEXT>
