<P>
WORLD IN BRIEF; CHINA; BEIJING LAW LIMITS DOGS TO 1 PER FAMILY 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Beijing's city government has decided to ban dogs from all public areas from 
dawn to dusk and to limit families -- at a high cost in annual fees -- to 
ownership of no more than one of man's best friends. The law, which takes 
effect May 1, limits every family to no more than one dog and requires Beijing 
citizens and foreigners to obtain approval from local police before they can 
keep a canine with an initial registration fee of $580. 
</P>
